WHITE PAPER: Universal Intelligence via Hierarchical Active Inference and Differentiable Architecture Optimization

Executive Summary
This white paper presents the complete mathematical foundation for a Universal Intelligence (UI) system that is both theoretically optimal and practically implementable. The framework unifies principles from information theory, dynamical systems, optimization theory, and neuroscience into a single coherent architecture that self-optimizes under resource constraints. The system represents the mathematical limit of what can be achieved given fundamental physical and computational constraints.

1. Introduction: The Universal Intelligence Problem
1.1 Problem Statement
The quest for Universal Intelligence has traditionally faced three fundamental challenges:
1. The Specification Problem: How to mathematically define intelligence without human bias
2. The Resource Problem: How to operate within finite computational resources
3. The Integration Problem: How to maintain coherence across multiple scales and modalities

1.2 Solution Overview
Our framework addresses these challenges through:
• Free Energy Minimization as the universal objective function
• Hierarchical Multi-Scale Architecture for computational tractability
• Differentiable Architecture Optimization for self-optimization
• Resource-Aware Constrained Optimization for practical implementation

2. Mathematical Foundations
2.1 Core Principles
Axiom 2.1.1 (Free Energy Principle)
All intelligent systems minimize variational free energy:
ℱ = D_KL[q(s) || p(s|o)] - log p(o)

Axiom 2.1.2 (Resource Boundedness)
ComputationalCost(System) ≤ R_total

Axiom 2.1.3 (Hierarchical Organization)
Δt⁽ˡ⁾ = κˡ · Δt⁽⁰⁾ for κ > 1

